In [5]:
# https://github.com/jbmouret/matplotlib_for_papers/blob/master/src/plot_variance_matplotlib_white.py
def clean_layout(ax):
    # Delete unnecessary lines
    ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines['left'].set_visible(False)

    try:
        # Remove frame color
        frame = ax.legend_.get_frame()
        frame.set_facecolor('1.0')
        frame.set_edgecolor('1.0')
    except:
        pass

    # y axis grid line
    ax.grid(axis='y', color="0.9", linestyle='-', linewidth=1)
    ax.set_axisbelow(True)
In [6]:
# save-related functions

# model file location
modelfilepath = '../models' # old name was modelpath

def save_CVmodel(model,X_train,modelname,version='1.0'):
    # Set the model info
    from sklearn import __version__ as sklearn_version
    import datetime
    
    best_model = model
    best_model.version = version
    best_model.pandas_version = pd.__version__
    best_model.numpy_version = np.__version__
    best_model.sklearn_version = sklearn_version
    best_model.X_columns = [col for col in X_train.columns]
    best_model.build_datetime = datetime.datetime.now()

    # save the model
    save_file(best_model,modelname, modelfilepath)
    
def saveFunc(model_path,X_train,model):
    if revisedFlag==True:
        save_CVmodel(model,X_train,model_path[10:],modelfilepath)
    else:
        print('The model was Not revised')
In [7]:
# Add the metrics to the ModelComparison
def addModel(df1,name,y_test,predictions,model=0):
    # Set a variable for Best para
    if model != 0:
        Best_para = model.best_params_ 
    else:
        Best_para = ''
    
    df2=pd.DataFrame([{'Model name':str(name),
                        'MAE':mean_absolute_error(y_test,predictions),
                        'RMSE':np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test,predictions)),
                        'Explained_variance_score':explained_variance_score(y_test,predictions),
                        'Best para': Best_para,
                      } 
                    ])
    return pd.concat([df1,df2],axis=0,ignore_index=True)
In [8]:
# define a function to load an existing model
def load_CVmodel(model_path,expected_model_version = '1.0'):
    import pickle
    from sklearn import __version__ as sklearn_version
    
    if os.path.exists(model_path):
        with open(model_path, 'rb') as f:
            model = pickle.load(f)
            print("Expected model version has been loaded")
        if model.version != expected_model_version:
            print("Expected model version doesn't match version loaded")
        if model.sklearn_version != sklearn_version:
            print("Warning: model created under different sklearn version")
        return model

    else:
        print("Expected model not found. Run the model fit")

Gradient Boosting w/ RandomizedSearchCV¶

Explaination about Gradient Boosting

Score in GradientBoostingRegressor

Define the pipeline¶

In [28]:
from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingRegressor
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline

gb_pipeline = Pipeline([
                ("st_scaler",StandardScaler()),
                ("gb_model",GradientBoostingRegressor())
                ])

RandomizedSearchCV¶

In [29]:
n_est = [int(n) for n in np.logspace(start=1, stop=3, num=20)]


# Create the parameter grid
param_grid = {
#     'st_scaler': [
#         StandardScaler(),
#         MinMaxScaler(), 
#         None,
#                  ],
    'gb_model__n_estimators': np.array(n_est), # learning rate per eta
    'gb_model__max_depth': np.arange(3, 20, 3), # max depth per tree
    'gb_model__learning_rate': np.arange(0.05, 1, 0.05),
    
}


# Perform RandomizedSearchCV
gb_rand_neg_mse = RandomizedSearchCV(
                        estimator=gb_pipeline,
                        param_distributions=param_grid,
                        n_iter=10,
                        scoring='neg_mean_squared_error', # The negative of "mean_squared_error" gives the lowest mse
                        cv=5,
                        verbose=1,
                        n_jobs=-1,
                        
)



# Define expected model info
model_path = '../models/GradientBoostingRegressor.pkl'

# Load a model, otherwise fit
if willReviseFlag==False:
    gb_rand_neg_mse = load_CVmodel(model_path)
    revisedFlag=False
else:
    # Fit the estimator
    gb_rand_neg_mse.fit(X_train, y_train)
    revisedFlag=True


    
# Compute metrics
print('Lowest(Best) RMSE: ',np.sqrt(np.abs(gb_rand_neg_mse.best_score_)))
print('Best model: ',gb_rand_neg_mse.best_estimator_)

XGBoost w/ RandomizedSearchCV¶

Define the pipeline¶

In [36]:
import xgboost as xgb
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline

# Regression(XGBRegressor)
xgb_pipeline = Pipeline([
                ("st_scaler",StandardScaler()),
                ("xgb_model",xgb.XGBRegressor(seed=42)),
                ])

# # Classification
# pipeline = Pipeline([
#                      ("featureunion", numeric_categorical_union),
#                      ("dictifier", Dictifier()),
#                      ("vectorizer", DictVectorizer(sort=False)),
#                      ("clf", xgb.XGBClassifier(max_depth=3)),
#                     ])

RandomizedSearchCV¶

ref: DC 14.5 sec4.2

In [37]:
# Create the parameter grid
param_grid = {
    'st_scaler': [
        StandardScaler(),
        MinMaxScaler(),
#         None
    ],
    
    'xgb_model__objective':['reg:linear'],
    'xgb_model__booster':["gbtree","gblinear"],
    'xgb_model__learning_rate': np.arange(0.05, 1, 0.05), # learning rate per eta
    'xgb_model__gamma':np.arange(.00, 1.5, .05), # min loss erduction to create new tree split
    'xgb_model__lambda':np.arange(.00, 1.5, .05), # L2 reg on leaf weights
    'xgb_model__alpha':np.arange(.00, 1.5, .05), # L1 reg on leaf weights
    'xgb_model__max_depth': np.arange(3, 20, 1), # max depth per tree
    'xgb_model__subsample':np.arange(.05, 1, .05), # %sample used per tree
    'xgb_model__colsample_bytree':np.arange(.1,1.0,.05), # efatures used per tree
    
    'xgb_model__n_estimators': np.array([int(n) for n in np.logspace(start=1, stop=3, num=20)])
}


# Perform RandomizedSearchCV
XGB_rand_neg_mse = RandomizedSearchCV(
                        estimator=xgb_pipeline,
                        param_distributions=param_grid,
                        n_iter=10,
                        scoring='neg_mean_squared_error', # The negative of "mean_squared_error" gives the lowest mse
                        cv=5,
                        verbose=1,
                        n_jobs=-1,
)

# Define expected model info
model_path = '../models/xgb.XGBRegressor.pkl'

# Load a model, otherwise fit
if willReviseFlag==False:
    XGB_rand_neg_mse = load_CVmodel(model_path)
    revisedFlag=False
else:
    # Fit the estimator
    XGB_rand_neg_mse.fit(X_train, y_train)
    revisedFlag=True
   
    
# Compute metrics
print('Lowest(Best) RMSE: ',np.sqrt(np.abs(XGB_rand_neg_mse.best_score_)))
print('Best model: ',XGB_rand_neg_mse.best_estimator_)

In [71]:
model = Sequential()

model.add(Dense(98,activation='relu')) #The layer we firstly try is the twoce of the #features(=28)
model.add(Dropout(0,2)) #To prevent overfitting, drpoout 20% of the input

model.add(Dense(49,activation='relu'))# The second and further layers willl be half of hte previous ones
model.add(Dropout(0,2))

model.add(Dense(24,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0,2))

model.add(Dense(1,activation='relu'))

model.compile(optimizer='adam',loss='mse')

BayesSearchCV ¶

We use this CV to explore the most promising hyperparameters in the problem-space

These are the references for this BayesSearchCV.

Optimising hyper-parameters efficiently with Scikit-Optimize

Machine Learning Mastery

Optimizing Hyperparameters the right Way

Scikit-learn hyperparameter search wrapper

BayesSearchCV (Skopt document)

The parameters for each search should be the same as the one in RandomisedSearchCV, but my PC caused some errors in this cnoditions. So, please keep in mind that some search area is narrower than those in RandomisedSearchCV.

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, MinMaxScaler

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor

from skopt.space import Real, Categorical, Integer

# Set the search parameter
rf_search = {
#     'rf__max_depth': Integer(1, 100, prior="log-uniform"),
#     'rf__max_features': Categorical(['auto', 'sqrt']),
#     'rf__min_samples_leaf': Integer(1, 4),
#     'rf__min_samples_split': Integer(2, 10),
    'rf__n_estimators': Integer(10, 100, prior="log-uniform"),
}
In [86]:
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from skopt import BayesSearchCV
# Build a pipeline
pipe = Pipeline([
#     ('gb', GradientBoostingRegressor()),
    ('rf', RandomForestRegressor()),
])

# Fit a ByesSearch
rf_opt = BayesSearchCV(
    pipe,
    [(rf_search, 20),],
    cv=5,
    scoring='neg_mean_squared_error',
    n_jobs=-1,
)

# Load a model if willReviseFlag is True, otherwise fit
model_path = '../models/rf_BayesSearchCV.pkl'
if willReviseFlag==False:
    rf_opt = load_CVmodel(model_path)
    revisedFlag=False
else:
    # Fit the estimator
    rf_opt.fit(X_train, y_train)
    revisedFlag=True

Stacking¶

The codes used here are from

  • "Stacking Ensemble Machine Learning With Python"
  • Combine predictors using stacking

Stacking ensemble with top 2 of the best existing models¶

Based on the table, ModelComparison, the top 2 models are followings.

  • RandomForestRegressor w/ RandomisedSearchCV (rf_rand_best)
  • GradientBoostingRegressor w/ RandomisedSearchCV (gb_rand_best)

In [104]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.ensemble import StackingRegressor


# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/45074698/how-to-pass-elegantly-sklearns-gridseachcvs-best-parameters-to-another-model
# get a stacking ensemble of models

# define the base models
level0 = [
    ('rf_rand_best', make_pipeline(rf_opt_best)),
    ('gb_rand_best', make_pipeline(gb_opt_best)),
]

# define meta learner model
level1 = LinearRegression()

# define the stacking ensemble
stack = StackingRegressor(estimators=level0, final_estimator=level1, cv=5)

# Fit the regressor to the training data
model_path = '../models/stack_opt.pkl'
if willReviseFlag==False:
    stack = load_CVmodel(model_path)
    revisedFlag=False
else:
    # And fit
    stack.fit(X_train, y_train)
    revisedFlag=True
stack.fit(X_train, y_train)
Out[104]:
StackingRegressor(cv=5,
                  estimators=[('rf_rand_best',
                               Pipeline(steps=[('randomforestregressor',
                                                RandomForestRegressor())])),
                              ('gb_rand_best',
                               Pipeline(steps=[('gradientboostingregressor',
                                                GradientBoostingRegressor(learning_rate=0.10939277870747974,
                                                                          max_depth=8,
                                                                          n_estimators=431))]))],
                  final_estimator=LinearRegression())
